==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inelegancy
<hw>In*el"e*gan*cy</hw>
<pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Inelegances</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>, <plw>Inelegancies</plw>
<pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>inelegantia</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>in⟦eacute⟧l⟦eacute⟧gance</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality of being inelegant; lack of elegance or
grace; lack of refinement, beauty, or polish in language, composition,
or manners.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The notorious <qex>inelegance</qex> of her figure.</q> <rj><qau>T.
Hook.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Anything inelegant; <as>as, <ex>inelegance</ex> of
style in literary composition</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inelegant</ent>⟦br⟧
